<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-annular-sectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Annular Sectors</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_exwf0176">
            <p xml:id="auto_xeha9kr2">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_76igsg9k">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_aapwzs1q">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9f342nar">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_cqa5l2jg">
                        2.6 Area of a Part of a Circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8rdx0269">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_z4igdb4b">
                        Determine the area of an annular sector in different situations. Apply the area of a part of a circle in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bbxkwgkm" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_cibigs5o">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vnzake5v" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_i9qwtkux">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_z2lqwmfk" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_5t3isa8x"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_mpktek07">
                        <p xml:id="auto_o3ph8kul">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that an annular sector is the region between two concentric sectors with different radii but the same central angle. Identify the variables <m>R</m> (outer radius), <m>r</m> (inner radius), and <m>\theta</m> (central angle).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_gd1glyt0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7hkhtrc4">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of an annular sector using the formula <m>A = \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi(R^2 - r^2)</m>. Square each radius first, then subtract, and multiply by the angle fraction.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_y6o2bm8w">
                        <p xml:id="auto_v8gyhe86">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving annular sectors such as windshield wipers, wind turbines, clock hands, and mechanical arms.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_w8xjn2iu">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-a-part-of-a-circle/area-of-annular-sectors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_baxbnv2y">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-a-part-of-a-circle/step-by-step-guide_area-of-annular-sectors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Discovering Annular Sectors</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_onlgkxxn">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_potff235">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_7p9o5uqq">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_2afh5qqc">
                    Work in groups
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_bt90k0s4">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_7mt4z3ti">
                    Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to mark the same angle on both circles. Ask probing questions: <q>What is the difference between the two sectors?</q> <q>How do we find the area of the remaining shape?</q> For struggling groups: <q>Let us find the area of the larger sector first. Then find the area of the smaller sector. What do we do next?</q> For early finishers: <q>Can you write a general formula for finding the area of any annular sector?</q> Guide students to articulate: <em>The area of an annular sector equals the area of the larger sector minus the area of the smaller sector.</em> Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_86wi7pho">
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_gj78l43f">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_yz8n5qer"><p xml:id="auto_09sl7kwn">What shape did you create when you placed the smaller sector on the larger one?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_gidge3yl"><p xml:id="auto_13srk1wg">How did you calculate the area of this shape?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_rulhzx3y"><p xml:id="auto_tw45xao0">What is the relationship between the two sectors?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_sv2yxa0f"><p xml:id="auto_91fnf7yz">Can you write a formula for finding the area of an annular sector?</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_297oaf34">
        <p xml:id="auto_tnmsls8x">
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_n8v4v78n">
            <term>What you require;</term> 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pl5x5nnl">
            <ul xml:id="auto_ltint0vt">
                <li xml:id="auto_o99ko2s8">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7r45pfqh">
                        Two circular paper cutouts (one smaller, one larger),
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mfkd6fv5">
                    <p xml:id="auto_3kfm29vt">
                        Scissors,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lkz1v2gc">
                    <p xml:id="auto_kqms7usk">
                        Protractor,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_x45wfbwd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_bo0y1ejj">
                        Ruler,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xk818fcp">
                    <p xml:id="auto_sqjjeeol">
                        Colored markers.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_07bkf0mf">
            <ol xml:id="auto_82r7bb08">
                <li xml:id="auto_xpk3cs3b">
                    <p xml:id="auto_pxj1wia2">
                        Take two circular cutouts of different sizes but with 
                        the same center.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_okavrmxg">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ko0pdhec">
                        Use a protractor to mark the same central 
                        angle <m>\theta</m> on both circles.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6rnf2m4a">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dhqylgxb">
                        Cut out the corresponding sectors from both circles.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0mwsgihn">
                    <p xml:id="auto_gn0bkibh">
                        Place the smaller sector on the larger 
                        one and observe the remaining shape.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5kns7ztd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_djn32u8f">
                        Measure and calculate the area of each sector using the 
                        formula and compare with your actual cutout.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g1b62m3e">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6ty8u3by">
                        Discuss with other groups how to get the area of the figure you have formed.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p xml:id="auto_kl7bh9fr">
        <m>\textbf{Extended Activity}</m>
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="auto_keba7g6o">
        <p xml:id="auto_oeme1fec">
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_yqau8aod">
            <term>Materials Needed:</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_2ndvxa6r">
            <ul xml:id="auto_1ouqlhew">
                <li xml:id="auto_bhzx48f2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_yt6xk1h0">
                        A car wiper blade (or a picture of one) like the one drawn below;
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ls7ls8go">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6klh1n6k">
                        A protractor
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qek72ro5">
                    <p xml:id="auto_956zynbw">
                        A ruler
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mkoimb27">
                    <p xml:id="auto_a6ok8bud">
                        A notebook and calculator
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <image width="60%">
        <latex-image label="Ann2">
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                % Sector (area swept by wiper)
                \fill[pattern=north east lines] (0,0) -- (100:16) arc (100:0:16) -- cycle;
                
                \fill[fill=white,very thick] (0,0) -- (100:14) arc (100:0:14) -- cycle;
                
                \fill[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (100:1) arc (100:0:1) -- cycle;

                

                % Lines for sector
                \draw [very thick] (0,0) -- (100:16);
                \draw [very thick] (0,0) -- (0:16);
                \draw  [very thick] (100:16) arc (100:0:16);

                % Angle label
                \node [right] at (0.9, 0.8) {$\theta$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;,below,blue,very thick] (0,-0.2)--(14,-0.2);
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;,below,blue,very thick] (14,-0.2)--(16,-0.2);


                % Wiper label
                \node[left] at (100:16) {Wiper};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
           
            
        </image>
        <p xml:id="auto_dxx5qegq">
            <ol xml:id="auto_wtmm82ss">
                <li xml:id="auto_0q9zo86v">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ipujl12i">
                        Find the dimensions of the following;
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_hdqwt1e2">
                        The length of the wiper blade.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_z98ibefi">
                        The pivot point to the base of the wiper blade.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_thhuinte">
                        The angle <m>\theta</m> is the angle through which the wiper moves.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_keu52f7w">
                    <p xml:id="auto_scrsx27r">
                        Use the formula:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_6288pxnh">
                        <md>
                            <mrow>A= \amp \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi(R^2-r^2) </mrow>
                        </md>
                        to calculate the area cleaned by the wiper.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_pfrcl14c">
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_nlgmdecm">
                    <p xml:id="auto_m9y9mam7">
                        Ask students in your group to observe whether the wiper 
                        covers all parts of the windshield equally.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_0i6433on">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_mrhqy9eq">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_v66h1ryx">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_uailgg49">
                    To formalise the annular sector formula and address misconceptions after students have shared their findings from the anchor activity.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_fgjs7kxh">
                <title>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_jlwbfnp0">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_4xwkbytm"><p xml:id="auto_0fp7qqoc"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use different angles for the two sectors.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> Both sectors must have the same central angle to form an annular sector.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_mfzn8lta"><p xml:id="auto_7xt4my0p"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The two circles can have different centres.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> The circles must be concentric (share the same centre).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_gjowcz14"><p xml:id="auto_tw4c8u1r"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I subtract the radii first, then square.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> You must square each radius first, then subtract: <m>R^2 - r^2</m>, not <m>(R - r)^2</m>.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_pfluk8bp"><p xml:id="auto_fkkv0yfc"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>An annular sector is the same as an annulus.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> An annular sector is part of an annulus, defined by a central angle.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_gmr02xjk">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
     <p xml:id="auto_05ljau5o">
        An <m>\textbf{annular sector}</m> is the region enclosed between two concentric sectors of a circle with different radii but
        the same central angle. It is similar to a sector but with a smaller sector removed from a larger one.
    </p>

    
           
    <image width="60%">
    <latex-image label="Ann1">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Define radii and angle
            \def\R{3}  % Outer radius
            \def\r{2}  % Inner radius
            \def\a{40} % Half of the total angle theta

            % Draw concentric circles
            \draw[dashed,very thick] (0,0) circle (\R);
            \draw[dashed,very thick] (0,0) circle (\r);
            
            % Draw annular sector
            \fill[green!30,very thick] (\a:\r) arc (\a:-\a:\r) -- (-\a:\R) arc (-\a:\a:\R) -- cycle;

            % Draw sector boundaries
            \draw[very thick, blue] (0,0) -- (\a:\R);
            \draw[thick, red] (0,0) -- (-\a:\R);
            \draw[thick] (\a:\R) arc (\a:-\a:\R);
            \draw[thick] (\a:\r) arc (\a:-\a:\r);

            % Draw angle arc (theta) touching both red radii
            \draw[thick, blue] (\a:1) arc (\a:-\a:1);
            
            % Label for theta
            \node[blue,right] at (1,0.3) {\Large $\theta$};

            % L
            \node at (\a+5:\R-0.3) {\Large $R$}; % Outer radius label
            \node[below] at (0.5,-0.7) {\Large $r$}; % Inner radius label
            \draw [very thick,blue,&lt;-&gt;]  (0,-0.1)--(1.4,-1.4);
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
    </image>

    <p xml:id="auto_bi2fhtee">
        Having the knowledge of the area of a sector and the area of an annulus it is very easy to identify the area of an 
        annular sector.
    </p>
            
   
    <p xml:id="auto_46yildd1">
        <m>\textbf{Area of an annular sector}</m>
    </p>

    <p xml:id="auto_tz76scxi">
        Area of an annular sector is: <me>A=\frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi(R^2-r^2)</me>
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_3wlw07pu">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_qmfvfswh">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_e0chwmli">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3l6dzs6a">
                    To apply the annular sector formula to real-world problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_yxfpnu2y">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_62hgpi0s">
                    Guide learners through the worked examples. Emphasize the steps: identify <m>R</m>, <m>r</m>, and <m>\theta</m> from the problem context, substitute into the formula <m>A = \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi(R^2 - r^2)</m>, and compute carefully. Remind learners to square each radius before subtracting.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_qixd1912">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_n4wt9ms6">
                A wind turbine blade sweeps through a central angle of <m>140^\circ</m>. The length 
                of the blade is <m>50\, m</m>, and the inner radius (distance from the 
                pivot to the base of the blade) is <m>10\, m</m>. Find the swept area.
            </p>
            
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_w2313sf4">
                The learger radius (<m>R</m>) <m>=50\,m</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_6fn74o1c">
                The inner radius (<m>r</m>)  <m>=10\,m</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_onhnbkvl">
                Angle subtended <m>=140^\circ</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_glq96gdw">
                <md>
                    <mrow>A= \amp \frac {140}{360} \times \pi (50^2-10^2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{7}{18} \times \frac{22}{7} (2\,500-100) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp   \frac{7}{18} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 2\,400</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 2933.333333 </mrow>
                    <mrow> ≈\amp 2\,933.3 \,m^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_572bsy9q">
                The turbine sweeps an area of approximately <m>2\,933.3 \,m^2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_dh8gjfqz">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_91cl5fyr">
                Find the area of the annular sector shown below. (Use <m>\pi= 3.142</m>)
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
            <latex-image label="Ann3">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                     % Draw the outer sector (R = 12 cm)
                    \filldraw[cyan!30 ,very thick] (0,0) -- (60:12) arc (60:0:12) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the inner sector (r = 8 cm)
                    \filldraw[white] (0,0) -- (60:8) arc (60:0:8) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the outer arc
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0:12);
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (60:12);
                    \draw[thick] (0:12) arc (0:60:12);

                    % Draw the inner arc
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0:8);
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (60:8);
                    \draw[thick] (0:8) arc (0:60:8);

                
                    

                    % Label the angle
                    \draw[thick] (1,0) arc (0:60:1);
                    \node at (20:1.5) {  $60^\circ$};
                    
                    \node [above] at (3,0.1) { $8$ cm};
                    
                    \node [below] at (3,-0.2) { $12$ cm};
                    \draw [below,&lt;-&gt;,blue,very thick] (0,-0.2)--(12,-0.2);
                    
                    \draw [below,&lt;-&gt;,blue,very thick] (0,0.1)--(8,0.1);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_hpycily5">
                <m>A= \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi(R^2-r^2)</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_mf9w8t14">
                <md>
                    <mrow> A=\amp \frac{60}{360} \times \pi(12^2-8^2) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{60}{360} \times 3.142 (144-64)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{6} \times 3.142\times 80 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp  \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times  40</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 41.89333333 </mrow>
                    <mrow> ≈\amp 41.89\,cm^2 </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_z4lnx2ro">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_n4ocodmh">
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_tg13mc0o">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_7wjjnlwc">
                    Individual work
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_3n4bmqum">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ohzsxadi">
                    Distribute the exit ticket questions. Learners work individually and silently. Collect responses at the end to inform future instruction. Review common errors in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_sd94oop9">
                <title>Exit Ticket Answer Key</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_aavatra7">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_tbsabtos"><p xml:id="auto_zegjeri3"><m>A = \frac{150}{360} \times \frac{22}{7}(15^2 - 5^2) = \frac{5}{12} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 200 \approx 261.90\,\text{cm}^2</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_bgdy6hl4"><p xml:id="auto_gw1yzwao"><m>A = \frac{110}{360} \times \frac{22}{7}(45^2 - 15^2) = \frac{11}{36} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 1800 \approx 1728.57\,\text{cm}^2</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_3yz3s4xc"><p xml:id="auto_pu2dsibf"><m>A = \frac{120}{360} \times \frac{22}{7}(40^2 - 10^2) = \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 1500 \approx 1571.43\,\text{cm}^2</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5xdtcdyp"><p xml:id="auto_hj6dg39o"><m>A = \frac{180}{360} \times \frac{22}{7}(8^2 - 2^2) = \frac{1}{2} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 60 \approx 94.29\,\text{m}^2</m></p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

