    <exercise  label="ex-calculating-areas-of-a-mechanical-arm-sweep">
        <stack label="stk-calculating-areas-of-a-mechanical-arm-sweep" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-6-Area-of-a-Part-of-a-Circle/2-6-3-Area-of-an-Annular-Sector/Calculating-Areas-of-a-Mechanical-Arm-Sweep.xml" />
    </exercise>

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A clock's minute hand moves <m>150^\circ </m> in <m>25</m> minutes. The minute 
                    hand is <m>15 \,cm</m> long, and the inner radius is <m>5 \,cm</m> Calculate the cleaned area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>261.7 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A windshield wiper moves through <m>110^\circ</m>. 
                    The blade is <m>45 \,cm</m> long, and the pivot distance is <m>15\, cm</m>.  Calculate the cleaned area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>1728.1 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                     A car wiper has an outer radius <m>=40 \,cm</m>, an  inner radius <m>r=10\,cm</m>, and a central angle <m>=120^\circ</m>. Find the area cleaned by the wiper?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>1571 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A mechanical arm sweeps through <m>180^\circ</m>. 
                    The outer radius is <m>8</m> m, and the inner radius is 
                    <m>2</m> m. Determine the area covered.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>94.26 \;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                The shaded region in the figure
                below shows the area swept out on a
                flat windscreen by a wiper.
                Calculate the area of this region.
                </p>
                <image width="60%">
            <latex-image  label="Ann4">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                    % Sector (area swept by wiper)
                    \fill[pattern=north east lines] (0,0) -- (100:16) arc (100:0:16) -- cycle;
                    
                    \fill[fill=white,very thick] (0,0) -- (100:14) arc (100:0:14) -- cycle;
                    
                    \fill[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (100:1) arc (100:0:1) -- cycle;

                    

                    % Lines for sector
                    \draw [very thick] (0,0) -- (100:16);
                    \draw [very thick] (0,0) -- (0:16);
                    \draw  [very thick] (100:16) arc (100:0:16);

                    % Angle label
                    \node [right] at (0.9, 0.8) {$120^\circ$};
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;,below,blue,very thick] (0,-0.2)--(14,-0.2);
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;,below,blue,very thick] (14,-0.2)--(16,-0.2);

                    % Length labels
                    \node[below] at (0:9) {16 cm};
                    \node[above left] at (100:14.5) {4 cm};

                    % Wiper label
                    \node[left] at (100:16) {Wiper};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>62.84 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_keokgh88">
                <title>For Struggling Learners</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ommr9ff7">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ujes03mh"><p xml:id="auto_6bdxhito">Provide pre-cut circular cutouts with sectors already outlined.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_34bid9di"><p xml:id="auto_4eq0bqhf">Use simpler angles and radii for initial practice.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zth95oc9"><p xml:id="auto_2cd7ro3s">Pair struggling learners with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_riezr8kc"><p xml:id="auto_p3bvmbr5">Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_23xo5vfs"><p xml:id="auto_japo0568">Allow use of calculators.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_sdcj2e7a"><p xml:id="auto_ag3754d5">Break down the formula into steps: find area of larger sector, find area of smaller sector, subtract.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_4z0rfvoj">
                <title>For On-Level Learners</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_i9hmseb4">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_9bhdd5y3"><p xml:id="auto_51qh1duv">Encourage learners to verify their formula with different angles and radii.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2qfhlghr"><p xml:id="auto_hlnjbufw">Ask learners to explain the relationship between annular sectors, sectors, and annuli.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zmg0ou98"><p xml:id="auto_h0v7p04z">Provide mixed practice with different types of annular sector problems.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_0r1bap3n"><p xml:id="auto_otaqfzk3">Challenge learners to solve problems where they need to find missing dimensions.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_e4q3663y">
                <title>For Advanced Learners</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_2b74r9fv">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_x0uie5lg"><p xml:id="auto_0ucpkl5q">Challenge learners to derive the formula algebraically.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_809y5mdn"><p xml:id="auto_ncld72jr">Explore real-world applications: wind turbines, windshield wipers, clock hands, mechanical arms.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_9np59r2b"><p xml:id="auto_4221m07s">Investigate the relationship between the angle and the area swept.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5nxoon7s"><p xml:id="auto_kxh6uhqk">Apply the concept to optimisation problems: given fixed radii, what angle maximises the area?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_q7sux38y"><p xml:id="auto_k9fl5w2i">Solve problems involving multiple annular sectors or composite shapes.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

